<dl id="n05028j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05028j">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05028j"> 28(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> soul of the rice <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05028j"><li>FW 34.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n05028j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n05028j">1939</a> &nbsp;<a href="../../flex/z/lexfh.htm#n05028j">FH IX</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05028j">MS BL 47472-98v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:007 <a name="b11d" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#b11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b11d.htm#n05028j">Draft: I.2&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Every supernatural religion, ancient and modern, has its magic food, its ritual meal, its Divine sacrifice. &hellip; In Buru, an island of the East Indian Archipelago, there is an ancient and Pagan tribe of Indians who partake of a sacramental repast which they describe as &lsquo;eating the <mark>soul of the rice</mark>.&rsquo; <small> J.T. Lloyd, <a name="GODE" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GODE"><cite title="source">God-Eating</cite></a>, (1921) 34</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
